  "title": "Quadratic orbit–stabilizer Shapiro.",
  "body": " Quadratic orbit stabilizer Shapiro   Let have coordinates with acting by left translation on . If is the -extension and is the scalar Shapiro coordinate, then the orbit classes of evaluate as follows. For , choose any lift and use the convention This is independent of the chosen lift and is the convention fixed in :    Lean (square)  Lean (free)  Lean (involution)  Lean (free, aux)  Lean (involution, aux)   We treat square orbits, free orbits, and involution-stabilized orbits in that order, recording at each stage whether the identity is literal at cochain level or only after passage to cohomology.  Choose lifts of , and write for the image of in . With the left-regular convention used here, the normalized Shapiro map is For scalar cocycles on , direct substitution into the normalized bar corestriction gives The factor set therefore gives . For the free orbit, the coordinate appearing in the monomial is the right shift . By this differs from by the explicit coboundary , and displays the resulting normalized boundary after taking the cup product and trace. Therefore holds in cohomology; it is a literal cochain identity whenever the chosen section is right- -equivariant.  Now let , let be right-coset representatives for , and put . For and , use the notation of . Let be the quotient map. The graph pullback of the explicit half-orbit cocycle is For completeness, choose the lifts compatibly so that for , and put Its image in is . In these conventions the normalized corestriction of a -cochain on is Let . Compatibility of the transversals gives and, for , Substituting the explicit two-point cocycle into gives exactly : its first summand is the oriented factor-set term, and its second summand is the orientation-reversal correction. Consequently as normalized cochains. By , the inner graph class is , which is denoted in field notation. Equation follows. With the compatible nested transversals just chosen, is literal equality of normalized cochains. For arbitrary choices, and give the two explicit normalized -cochains whose boundaries account for the change. Hence the formulas evaluate the actual orbit classes used in , including all -terms, without an unspecified convention-dependent ambiguity.   "
