  "body": " Targets with only trivial module factors   Suppose every chief factor of is a trivial -module. Let be the maximal -quotient of and let . Then has odd order, has a unique normal lift centralizing , and Projection to identifies exact-image subgroups of projecting onto with subgroups that map onto .   Lean  Lean   We construct and characterize the odd-order complement, identify as a fibre product, and then classify the exact-image subgroups.  The kernel has odd order by . Let be its inverse image in . Schur Zassenhaus gives a complement . Along a -chief series triviality of every factor gives . Hence . Coprime action gives Thus . Schur Zassenhaus conjugacy says that all complements are -conjugate; since centralizes , the complement is unique and therefore normal in .   In more detail: every element of the inverse image of has a commuting factorization , with of odd order and of -power order. Coprimality shows that such a product has odd order exactly when . Thus is intrinsically the set of odd-order elements in this subgroup. This characterization is preserved by conjugation, giving normality and uniqueness at once.  The quotient is a -group. The two quotient maps define Its kernel lies in both and , hence is trivial, and the two groups have the same order. This proves .   The same parity separation explains the decoration: every homomorphism to the exponent-two group kills , so the decoration descends to . A subgroup of the resulting fibre product that surjects to both factors has kernels of coprime orders; the coprime subdirect-product lemma therefore forces it to be the whole fibre product.  If projects onto and , then . Inside , the subgroup projects onto both factors. The two kernels have odd and -power orders, so gives . Conversely, for every subgroup mapping onto , the fibre product is a subgroup of projecting onto .   "
